  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, lived experience for many people who feel their identity might undermine their performance. As a mother of three, I've seen how deeply personal and impactful these dynamics can be. Growing up in a family where both parents had vocational training but not advanced degrees, I never had the same academic confidence as my peers who came from more traditional educational backgrounds. That sense of 'not belonging' in subjects like math or science isn't just about ability; it's about the fear that your group's stereotypes will overshadow your potential. I've seen this play out in my own life when I've tried to engage with technical topics at work—my hands-on approach, rooted in practical experience, often gets mislabeled as 'not serious enough.' The problem isn't that people aren't smart enough; it's that the system doesn't account for how identity and self-perception can affect performance. We need to address this by creating spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes, not by labeling them as 'less capable.' For instance, in my role as a server, I've noticed how people often feel intimidated by technical discussions. If we could frame these conversations in ways that honor everyone's strengths—like using storytelling or hands-on examples instead of jargon—everyone could feel more confident. Addressing stereotype threat requires empathy and practical steps: training educators to recognize unconscious bias, creating mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share their backgrounds, and simply normalizing the idea that it's okay to not know everything. The key is to focus on building community, not just fixing individual problems.",
